  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 蕀 : '
    value: 棘
english:
  title: Passing Yeoju by Boat on the Way to Take Office in Seoнsan After Illness—Climbing Cheongshim Tower but Missing the Host, I Return Hastily to the Boat and Compose Verses Following the Rhyme Scheme of Gajeong
  author: Kim Jong-jik
  language: eng
  text: |-
    My boat is moored at the edge of a thatched house, where thorns form the fence.
    How could fish and birds have known my face so long ago?
    After my illness, I can still gather staff and shoes,
    And in my exile, I am only now granted a glimpse of these mountains.

    Ten years of worldly affairs have passed in lonely verses,
    While August's autumn colors scatter through the tangled trees.
    For a moment I lean against the railing, gazing northward,
    But the boatman urges departure—I am not allowed to rest.
  footnotes:
    - This poem was written during Kim Jong-jik's journey to assume a new official position after recovering from illness. The speaker's inability to meet the host at Cheongshim Tower and his hurried return to the boat become occasions for reflection on exile, aging, and the fleeting nature of freedom to wander.
    - The reference to 'ten years' and exile suggests the poet's difficult political circumstances and sense of displacement, common themes in Korean literati poetry of this period.
    - The final image of the boatman's urging conveys both the practical constraints of travel and a deeper sense of life's relentless forward motion—the speaker cannot linger even in moments of beauty and contemplation.
